# Organization and administration

Caltech operates as an incorporated non-profit corporation, a structure that underscores its mission-driven, rather than profit-oriented, objectives. Its governance is meticulously overseen by a privately appointed [board of trustees](/Board_of_directors), comprising 46 distinguished members. These trustees serve five-year terms of office, with a mandatory retirement age of 72, ensuring a consistent influx of fresh perspectives and expertise [23] [64]. Among their most critical responsibilities, the trustees elect a president, who functions as the chief executive officer of the institute, charged with the comprehensive administration of its affairs on behalf of the board. Complementing this leadership, a provost is appointed to serve as the chief academic officer, reporting directly to the president. The administrative hierarchy is further stratified with the appointment of ten additional vice presidential and other senior positions, each overseeing specific crucial functions of the institute [64]. [Thomas F. Rosenbaum](/Thomas_Felix_Rosenbaum) assumed the mantle as Caltech's ninth president in 2014, guiding the institution through its current era. The substantial [endowment](/Financial_endowment) of Caltech, a vital financial bedrock, is managed with rigorous oversight by a permanent trustee committee and expertly administered by a dedicated investment office.

The institute itself is meticulously structured into six primary academic divisions, each a specialized hub of intellectual pursuit: Biology and Biological Engineering (established in 1927), Chemistry and Chemical Engineering (founded in 1926), Engineering and Applied Science (also founded in 1926), Geological and Planetary Sciences (established in 1927), Humanities and Social Sciences (founded in 1926), and Physics, Mathematics, and Astronomy (established in 1926). Given Caltech's formidable historical prestige and the often-compact size of its faculty within many major fields, the institution exercises an exceptionally stringent and deliberate process in selecting candidates for its academic positions. This rigorous vetting can, at times, result in certain positions remaining unfilled for several years, a testament to the uncompromising standards maintained until precisely the right candidate, possessing the requisite intellectual caliber and research alignment, is identified [65]. Caltech, in a demonstration of its commitment to academic excellence, dedicates significant financial and institutional resources to not only attract top-tier faculty but also to provide them with substantial support, thereby fostering an environment conducive to groundbreaking research and ambitious academic endeavors [66]. The voting faculty of Caltech comprises all professors, instructors, research associates and fellows, and, notably, the University Librarian, underscoring the broad academic participation in governance. This faculty collective is entrusted with the critical responsibilities of establishing admission requirements, defining academic standards, and shaping curricula. The Faculty Board, serving as the faculty's representative body, consists of 18 elected faculty representatives, augmented by other senior administration officials, ensuring diverse academic input. Full-time professors are expected to uphold a multifaceted role, encompassing teaching duties, conducting pioneering research, providing mentorship and guidance to students, and undertaking essential administrative work, such as serving on vital institutional committees [67].

Established in the 1930s, the [Jet Propulsion Laboratory](/Jet_Propulsion_Laboratory) (JPL) stands as a testament to Caltech's deep involvement in space exploration. It functions as a [federally funded research and development center](/Federally_funded_research_and_development_center) (FFRDC), uniquely owned by [NASA](/NASA) and operated as a distinct division of Caltech through a meticulously defined contract between the space agency and the institute. In 2008, JPL's expenditures on research and development exceeded a staggering $1.6 billion, employing a formidable workforce of over 5,000 project-related and support personnel [68]. The Director of JPL also holds the title of a Caltech Vice President, a dual role that underscores the integrated nature of the relationship, and is directly accountable to the President of the Institute for the comprehensive management and strategic direction of the laboratory [69].

In a rather contemporary development, December 2023 saw graduate students and postdoctoral researchers at Caltech file for recognition to engage in collective bargaining, forming Caltech Grad researchers and Postdocs United, in affiliation with the [United Auto Workers](/United_Auto_Workers) (C/GPU-UAW). This move, perhaps an inevitable evolution in academic labor relations, led to a vote conducted by the [National Labor Relations Board](/National_Labor_Relations_Board) (NLRB) on January 31 and February 1, 2024. The results, certified by the NLRB in February 2024, showed a decisive outcome: 1335 out of 1997 eligible workers participated, with a significant 78% voting in favor of unionization. This paved the way for contract negotiations, which officially commenced in May 2024 [70]. As a further demonstration of their collective resolve, in December 2024, C/GPU-UAW members held a strike authorization vote [71], with 1441 members participating and an overwhelming 86% voting in favor of empowering their bargaining team to call a strike if future negotiations necessitate such action [72]. It appears even the most brilliant minds occasionally need to assert their material interests.

# Academics

Caltech proudly maintains its identity as a small, four-year, intensely residential research university, distinguished by a student body where graduate programs slightly outnumber undergraduate enrollments [73]. This emphasis on advanced study underscores its commitment to high-level research and specialized education. The institute has been rigorously accredited by the [Western Association of Schools and Colleges](/Western_Association_of_Schools_and_Colleges) since 1949, a testament to its consistent adherence to high academic standards [74] [75]. Academically, Caltech operates on the demanding [quarter system](/Academic_term) [76], a structure that necessitates a rapid pace of learning and adaptation. Under this system, the fall term typically commences in late September and concludes just before Christmas, allowing a brief reprieve. The second term then begins promptly after New Year's Day and runs until mid-March, followed by the third term, which starts in late March or early April and extends through early June [77]. This continuous cycle ensures a concentrated and intensive academic experience.

## Undergraduate admissions

Admission to Caltech is not merely competitive; it is, quite frankly, extraordinarily rigorous, a fact that becomes abundantly clear when examining the statistics. Prior to its temporary shift to a test-blind policy, Caltech consistently attracted students who boasted the highest standardized test scores in the entire nation, a clear indicator of the exceptional academic caliber of its applicant pool [85] [86]. For admissions to the Class of 2028 (who will be entering in 2024), Caltech distinguished itself as the hardest college in America to gain acceptance to, recording an all-time low admit rate of a mere 2.7% [87]. This figure, while daunting, is a stark reflection of the intense demand for a Caltech education.

For the freshmen who enrolled in 2019 (the Class of 2023), the middle 50% range for [SAT](/SAT) scores was an impressive 740–780 for evidence-based reading and writing, and an almost perfect 790–800 for mathematics, culminating in a total composite score range of 1530–1570. Similarly, for the [ACT](/ACT_(test)) Composite score, the middle 50% range was a formidable 35–36. Prospective students also faced subject-specific hurdles, with the SAT Math Level 2 middle 50% range being a perfect 800–800. For the SAT Physics, Chemistry, and Biology Subject Tests, the middle 50% ranges were consistently high, falling between 760–800 for each [88]. In June 2020, in response to global disruptions, Caltech announced a temporary test-blind policy, stating it would neither require nor consider standardized test scores for the subsequent two years. This moratorium was subsequently extended twice, beginning in July 2021, before being ultimately cancelled, with the standardized test requirement reinstated for applicants to the Class of 2029 and beyond [89] [90]. For domestic applicants, the institute proudly maintains a [need-blind](/Need-blind) admissions policy, meaning a student's financial need does not factor into their admission decision [91].

For the Class of 2027, who ultimately enrolled in Fall 2023, Caltech received an astounding 13,136 applications. From this vast pool, a mere 412 applicants were extended offers of admission, resulting in an exceptionally low admit rate of 3.14%; of those accepted, 270 ultimately chose to enroll [92] [93]. The following year, for the Class of 2028, Caltech further tightened its admissions, reducing the number of available seats by nearly one hundred. Out of approximately 13,000 total applications, only 315 applicants were accepted [93] [94]. In terms of diversity for the Class of 2025, 32% of enrolled students identified as being of underrepresented ancestry (a category encompassing students who self-identify as American Indian/Alaska Native, Hispanic/Latino, Black/African American, and/or Native Hawaiian/Pacific Islander), while 6% were international students [88].

