## Tuition and financial aid

For the 2021–2022 academic year, the undergraduate tuition at Caltech was set at $56,394. When factoring in all associated annual costs, excluding the Caltech Student Health Insurance Plan, the estimated total reached $79,947 [95]. Financial aid is a significant component of supporting students at Caltech. In the 2012–2013 academic year, the institute awarded a substantial $17.1 million in need-based aid, supplemented by $438,000 in non-need-based aid, and an additional $2.51 million in self-help support to its enrolled undergraduate students. For those students eligible for aid, the average financial aid package provided was a considerable $38,756. Despite the generous aid, students still graduated with an average debt of $15,090, a figure that, while manageable for many, still represents a significant investment in their education [76].

## Undergraduate program

The undergraduate program at Caltech is a demanding, full-time, four-year curriculum that places an unequivocal emphasis on rigorous instruction in the arts and sciences, distinguishing itself with a notably high degree of graduate coexistence, where advanced research often intertwines with undergraduate learning [73]. Caltech offers its undergraduates a choice of 28 distinct majors, which the institution formally refers to as "options," alongside 17 minors, spanning all six of its formidable academic divisions [96] [97]. Beyond these traditional pathways, Caltech also provides highly specialized interdisciplinary programs in fields such as Applied Physics, Biochemistry, Bioengineering, Computation and Neural Systems, Control and Dynamical Systems, Environmental Science and Engineering, Geobiology and Astrobiology, Geochemistry, and Planetary Astronomy—each designed to foster a holistic, multi-faceted approach to complex scientific problems. Historically, and indeed currently, the most perennially popular options among undergraduates include Chemical Engineering, Computer Science, Electrical Engineering, Mechanical Engineering, and Physics [98]. For the graduating class of 2023, the leading choices for majors were Computer Science, Mechanical Engineering, Physics, and Electrical Engineering, reflecting enduring student interest in these foundational and rapidly evolving fields.

All undergraduates are mandated to complete a rigorous core curriculum, meticulously designed to provide a foundational bedrock of knowledge and analytical prowess. This core, typically completed within the first two years of study, comprises 108 units, ensuring a robust grounding in science, mathematics, humanities, and physical education, all aimed at cultivating essential analytical and interdisciplinary skills. Specifically, it includes three terms of mathematics, three terms of physics, two terms of chemistry, one term of biology, a one-term "menu" course (allowing some choice), one term of computer science, a comprehensive scientific writing requirement, one term of physical education, and a substantial eleven terms dedicated to humanities and social science courses. To accommodate students with prior advanced knowledge, placement exams are available, allowing them to substitute introductory courses if they demonstrate proficiency. Furthermore, to ease the intense academic pressure during the initial transition, a pass/no-record grading system is implemented for the freshman fall term [99]. Prior to the entering class of 2013, Caltech's core curriculum was even more extensive, requiring five terms each of mathematics and physics, two terms of chemistry, one term of biology, two terms of laboratory courses, one term of scientific communication, three terms of physical education, and twelve terms of humanities and social science. Since 2013, the institute-wide requirement has been reduced to three terms each of mathematics and physics, with the remaining two terms in each discipline now mandated by specific "options" (majors) [100] [101].

A typical class at Caltech is assigned a value of 9 academic units. Given the extensive requirements of the core curriculum, coupled with the specialized degree requirements of individual options, students must, on average, undertake a formidable 40.5 units per term—meaning more than four classes—to successfully graduate within the traditional four-year timeframe. A course load of 36 units is considered the minimum for full-time enrollment, while 48 units is already regarded as a heavy load. Any registration exceeding 51 units necessitates a formal overload petition, a clear indication of the academic intensity [102]. Despite this demanding schedule, approximately 20 percent of students admirably pursue a double-major [103]. This impressive feat is largely achievable because the humanities and social sciences majors have been thoughtfully structured to be pursued in conjunction with a science major, fostering interdisciplinary excellence. While choosing two options within the same academic division is generally discouraged, it is not entirely impossible, allowing for highly specialized academic paths.

First-year students are strategically placed into their initial term classes based on their performance in a series of comprehensive placement exams covering mathematics, physics, chemistry, and writing. Furthermore, all classes taken during their first two terms are graded on a Pass/Fail basis [102], a system designed to mitigate the initial stress of the academic transition and encourage exploration rather than cutthroat competition. Indeed, the academic environment at Caltech fosters a spirit of collaboration; working together on [homework](/Homework) assignments is not only permitted but actively encouraged. This ethos, coupled with a deeply ingrained honor system, allows for the unique privilege of take-home tests and flexible homework schedules [104]. Beyond its core offerings, Caltech also provides valuable co-operative programs with other esteemed institutions, such as the nearby Pasadena [Art Center College of Design](/Art_Center_College_of_Design) and [Occidental College](/Occidental_College), broadening the scope of educational opportunities for its students.

According to a 2018 [PayScale](/PayScale) study, Caltech graduates demonstrate a remarkable earning potential, with a median early career salary of $83,400, which escalates to an impressive $143,100 mid-career. These figures collectively position Caltech alumni in the top 5 among graduates of all U.S. colleges and universities, underscoring the significant financial return on investment of a Caltech degree [105]. The average net return on investment over a substantial period of 20 years is calculated to be $887,000, ranking it as the tenth-highest among all U.S. colleges [106]. For students interested in military service, Caltech offers both Army and Air Force [ROTC](/ROTC) programs, facilitated through a cooperative arrangement with the [University of Southern California](/University_of_Southern_California) [76].

## Graduate program

Admission to Caltech's graduate programs is, predictably, an intensely competitive process, demanding not only exceptional academic achievement but also a profound alignment of interests. The faculty meticulously evaluate a range of factors, including the applicant's prior academic preparation, their demonstrated research experience, the specificity of their scientific interests, and the strength of recommendations provided by teachers or mentors [107]. A particularly critical aspect of the admission process is the precise matching of faculty research interests with those of the applicant, ensuring a symbiotic relationship conducive to advanced scholarly work. Historically, many graduate programs mandated the submission of GRE scores. However, in recent years, a growing number of departments have either made the GRE optional or, in a move towards more holistic review, no longer require it at all [108].

The graduate instructional programs at Caltech are predominantly focused on doctoral studies, reflecting the institution's deep commitment to producing leading researchers. These programs are, perhaps unsurprisingly, heavily concentrated in the demanding fields of science, technology, engineering, and mathematics (STEM) [73]. The institute offers a comprehensive suite of graduate degree programs, including the Master of Science, the Engineer's Degree, the Doctor of Philosophy, and integrated BS/MS and MD/PhD pathways, with the overwhelming majority of students pursuing the rigorous PhD program [73]. The most sought-after options at the graduate level mirror some undergraduate trends, with Chemistry, Physics, Biology, Electrical Engineering, and Chemical Engineering consistently proving to be the most popular choices [98].

Upon initial enrollment, most new graduate students are judiciously assigned a temporary advisor. This provisional arrangement allows students a crucial period of exploration and adjustment, affording them sufficient time to thoroughly investigate various research avenues and ultimately select a permanent advisor whose expertise and research align perfectly with their evolving scientific interests [109]. To further assist in this critical matching process, some graduate options incorporate structured rotations through different research laboratories. These rotations provide invaluable hands-on experience and facilitate a more informed decision regarding which faculty research group best suits the students' scientific inclinations. In certain options, students are permitted up to three such rotations during their demanding first year, maximizing their exposure to diverse research environments.

Caltech is committed to ensuring a smooth transition for its incoming graduate students, offering a range of on-campus housing options. All new graduate students are guaranteed housing during their inaugural year, with a variety of living experiences designed to cater to different needs and preferences [110]. Approximately half of Caltech's total graduate student population chooses to reside in campus housing, a testament to the convenience and community it offers. For students beyond their first year, continued on-campus housing is determined through a lottery system, with the results typically announced two months prior to the current housing contract end date. This considerate timing provides ample opportunity for those who may need to seek off-campus housing to make alternative arrangements [111].

The extensive and cutting-edge research facilities at Caltech are readily accessible to its graduate students, providing an unparalleled environment for scientific discovery. However, the opportunities for advanced research extend beyond the immediate campus. Students are also afforded the chance to work in the facilities of other distinguished universities, at leading research centers such as [NASA](/NASA)'s renowned [Jet Propulsion Laboratory](/Jet_Propulsion_Laboratory), and within innovative private industries, thereby broadening their exposure and collaborative networks [112]. The institute maintains an impressive graduate student to faculty ratio of 4:1, ensuring close mentorship and individualized attention [113]. Furthermore, Caltech actively participates in joint programs with other prestigious medical institutions, including the [Keck School of Medicine of the University of Southern California](/Keck_School_of_Medicine_of_USC), the [UCLA David Geffen School of Medicine](/UCLA_David_Geffen_School_of_Medicine), and the [Kaiser Permanente Bernard J. Tyson School of Medicine](/Kaiser_Permanente_Bernard_J._Tyson_School_of_Medicine). These collaborations offer highly selective MD/PhD degrees, allowing students to undertake their preclinical and clinical work at [USC](/University_of_Southern_California), [UCLA](/UCLA), or [KPSOM](/Kaiser_Permanente_Bernard_J._Tyson_School_of_Medicine), while simultaneously pursuing their demanding PhD research with any member of the distinguished Caltech faculty, encompassing the Biology, Chemistry, and Engineering and Applied Sciences Divisions. The MD degree is conferred by the respective medical school, while the PhD is proudly awarded by Caltech [114] [115].

Financial support for doctoral students at Caltech is remarkably comprehensive, with approximately 99 percent of all doctoral students receiving full financial assistance. This robust support system is typically structured through various mechanisms, including prestigious fellowships, research assistantships (which often integrate students directly into faculty research projects), teaching assistantships (providing valuable pedagogical experience), or a strategic combination of fellowship and assistantship support, ensuring that financial constraints do not impede the pursuit of advanced scientific inquiry [116].

Graduate students, much like their undergraduate counterparts, are bound by the same stringent yet empowering honor code, which famously permits the use of take-home examinations, fostering an environment of trust and academic integrity [117]. Any potential violations of this code within the graduate community are meticulously overseen and adjudicated by the dedicated Graduate Honor Council, ensuring that the principles of fairness and ethical conduct are consistently upheld.

## Rankings

Caltech consistently distinguishes itself on the global academic stage, frequently being ranked within the top ten universities worldwide by the most reputable and influential ranking bodies. This includes prominent positions in the [Times Higher Education World University Rankings](/Times_Higher_Education_World_University_Rankings), the [QS World University Rankings](/QS_World_University_Rankings), and the [Academic Ranking of World Universities](/Academic_Ranking_of_World_Universities) [128]. Such consistent high placement is a testament to its unwavering commitment to research excellence, academic rigor, and global impact.

For the 2022 academic cycle, [U.S. News & World Report](/U.S._News_%26_World_Report) recognized Caltech as tied for 9th among national universities in the United States overall. Beyond this general ranking, it was also notably placed 11th for being among the most innovative institutions and 15th for offering the best value [129]. In a further testament to its specialized strengths, U.S. News & World Report also ranked Caltech's graduate programs in Chemistry and Earth Sciences as the very best, securing the top position among all national universities [130].

