# Research

Caltech is unequivocally [classified](/Carnegie_Classification_of_Institutions_of_Higher_Education) among "R1: Doctoral Universities – Very High Research Activity," a designation that speaks volumes about its formidable research output and impact [131]. Its election to the esteemed [Association of American Universities](/Association_of_American_Universities) in 1934 further solidified its standing as a premier research university, maintaining a consistently "very high" level of research activity, predominantly concentrated in the critical [STEM fields](/STEM_fields) [12] [73]. The institution manages a substantial portfolio of research expenditures, amounting to $270 million annually [132], a figure that placed it 66th among all universities in the U.S. and an impressive 17th among private institutions without medical schools in 2008 [133] [134].

The lion's share of federal agencies contributing to Caltech's extensive research endeavors includes, but is certainly not limited to, [NASA](/NASA), the [National Science Foundation](/National_Science_Foundation), the [Department of Health and Human Services](/United_States_Department_of_Health_and_Human_Services), the [Department of Defense](/United_States_Department_of_Defense), and the [Department of Energy](/United_States_Department_of_Energy) [135]. These diverse funding sources underscore the breadth and national importance of Caltech's scientific contributions. In 2008 alone, Caltech received a significant breakdown of federal funding: $144 million was allocated to the physical sciences, $40.8 million to the life sciences, $33.5 million to engineering, $14.4 million to environmental sciences, $7.16 million to computer sciences, and $1.97 million to mathematical sciences [136].

The institute achieved an all-time high in research funding in 2009, securing an impressive $357 million [137]. Furthermore, as of the 2011 update, active funding from the [National Science Foundation](/National_Science_Foundation) Directorate of Mathematical and Physical Science (MPS) for Caltech stood at a remarkable $343 million. This figure is not only the highest for any single educational institution in the nation but also surpasses the total funds allocated to any individual state, with the sole exceptions of California and New York, a stark illustration of Caltech's disproportionate impact on national scientific funding [138].

In 2005, Caltech dedicated a substantial 739,000 square feet (68,700 m2) of its physical infrastructure specifically to research activities. This impressive allocation was strategically distributed, with 330,000 square feet (30,700 m2) devoted to the physical sciences, 163,000 square feet (15,100 m2) to engineering, and 160,000 square feet (14,900 m2) to the biological sciences [139]. This dedicated space ensures that researchers have the necessary facilities to pursue their ambitious projects.

Beyond its main campus, Caltech oversees and operates a network of world-class observatories and laboratories, extending its scientific reach across various disciplines and geographical locations. These include the renowned [Palomar Observatory](/Palomar_Observatory) in [San Diego County](/San_Diego_County,_California), which houses the powerful Hale Telescope; the [Owens Valley Radio Observatory](/Owens_Valley_Radio_Observatory) in [Bishop, California](/Bishop,_California), a crucial site for radio astronomy; the [Submillimeter Observatory](/Caltech_Submillimeter_Observatory) and the [W. M. Keck Observatory](/W._M._Keck_Observatory) perched atop the majestic [Mauna Kea Observatory](/Mauna_Kea_Observatory) in Hawaii; the groundbreaking [Laser Interferometer Gravitational-Wave Observatory](/LIGO) with facilities in [Livingston, Louisiana](/Livingston,_Louisiana) and [Richland, Washington](/Richland,_Washington); and the [Kerckhoff Marine Laboratory](/Kerckhoff_Marine_Laboratory) located in [Corona del Mar, California](/Corona_del_Mar,_California), dedicated to marine biology and oceanography [67]. The Institute further expanded its research infrastructure with the launch of the Kavli Nanoscience Institute at Caltech in 2006 [140], followed by the establishment of the [Keck Institute for Space Studies](/Keck_Institute_for_Space_Studies) in 2008. Moreover, Caltech continues to serve as the current intellectual home for the esteemed [Einstein Papers Project](/Einstein_Papers_Project), meticulously preserving and publishing the works of [Albert Einstein](/Albert_Einstein). The Spitzer Science Center (SSC), an integral component of the [Infrared Processing and Analysis Center](/Infrared_Processing_and_Analysis_Center) situated on the Caltech campus, functions as the primary data analysis and community support hub for [NASA](/NASA)'s sophisticated [Spitzer Space Telescope](/Spitzer_Space_Telescope).

In a testament to its commitment to translational research, Caltech forged a strategic partnership with [UCLA](/UCLA) to establish the Joint Center for Translational Medicine (UCLA-Caltech JCTM). This collaborative center is dedicated to conducting experimental research focused on direct clinical applications, encompassing the diagnosis and treatment of a wide range of diseases, most notably cancer. This partnership, initiated in 1997, also extends to the vital training of physician-scientists, bridging the gap between fundamental research and practical medical innovation [141].

Caltech also plays an active role in global environmental monitoring, operating several [TCCON](/Total_Carbon_Column_Observing_Network) stations as part of an international collaborative effort aimed at precisely measuring greenhouse gases on a global scale. One of these critical stations is conveniently located directly on the Caltech campus, providing valuable local data.

Undergraduates at Caltech are not merely encouraged but are actively expected to immerse themselves in research. A striking approximately 80% of the graduating class of 2010 participated in research through the annual Summer Undergraduate Research Fellowships (SURF) program at least once during their academic tenure, with many opting to continue their research pursuits throughout the regular school year [142]. Students are empowered to conceive and submit their own SURF proposals for research projects, working in close collaboration with professors, fostering a deep sense of ownership and mentorship. Approximately 70 percent of applicants are successfully awarded SURFs, a testament to the program's accessibility and reach. The program is open to both Caltech students and undergraduates from other institutions, further broadening its impact. This extensive undergraduate research engagement serves as invaluable preparation for graduate school and is a key factor in why Caltech boasts the highest percentage of alumni who go on to receive a PhD among all major universities [143].

The intricate process of licensing and transferring technology developed within Caltech's hallowed halls to the commercial sector is expertly managed by the Office of [Technology Transfer](/Technology_Transfer) (OTT). The OTT plays a crucial role in safeguarding and managing the invaluable intellectual property generated by faculty members, students, other researchers, and the innovative technologists at JPL. Impressively, Caltech consistently receives more invention disclosures per faculty member than any other university in the nation, a clear indicator of its prolific innovative output [144]. As of the 2008 update, a remarkable 1891 patents had been granted to Caltech researchers since 1969, underscoring the institution's profound impact on technological advancement and intellectual property creation [145].

# Students

For the 2024–2025 academic year, Caltech enrolled a total of 987 undergraduate students and 1,443 graduate students, reflecting its characteristic emphasis on advanced study and research [5]. In terms of gender representation, women constituted 45% of the undergraduate student body and 36% of the graduate student body, indicating a continued, albeit gradual, movement towards gender parity [5]. The racial demographics of the student population at Caltech present a notable divergence from those of the nation as a whole [147], illustrating a distinct profile that reflects both selective admissions and the institution's specific outreach efforts.

The four-year graduation rate at Caltech stands at 79%, while the six-year rate rises to 92% [76]. These figures, while respectable, are comparatively lower than those observed at most other leading U.S. universities [148]. However, it is crucial to note that these rates represent a substantial improvement from the much lower figures recorded in the 1960s and 1970s [149], indicating significant progress in student support and retention. Moreover, students pursuing degrees in [STEM fields](/STEM_fields) traditionally exhibit graduation rates below 70% across national averages [150], suggesting that Caltech's rates, within the context of its rigorous STEM focus, are quite robust.

