# Student life

## House system

During the early decades of the 20th century, a dedicated Caltech committee undertook a comprehensive tour of several prominent universities across the nation. Their objective was to meticulously study best practices in student living arrangements, ultimately concluding that the institution's undergraduate housing system should transition from the traditional [fraternities](/Fraternities_and_sororities) to a more integrated [residential college](/Residential_college) model, fostering a cohesive and academically supportive community. This vision materialized with the construction of the initial four South Houses (or *Hovses*, as they are quaintly styled in the enduring stone engravings): [Blacker House](/House_System_at_the_California_Institute_of_Technology), [Dabney House](/House_System_at_the_California_Institute_of_Technology), [Fleming House](/House_System_at_the_California_Institute_of_Technology), and [Ricketts House](/House_System_at_the_California_Institute_of_Technology). As the student body grew and evolved, so too did the residential landscape. In the 1960s, three additional North Houses were constructed: [Lloyd House](/House_System_at_the_California_Institute_of_Technology), [Page House](/Page_House_(Caltech)), and [Ruddock House](/House_System_at_the_California_Institute_of_Technology). Further expansion occurred in the 1990s with the addition of [Avery House](/House_System_at_the_California_Institute_of_Technology). The four original South Houses underwent extensive renovations, closing in 2005 and triumphantly reopening in 2006, modernized yet retaining their historic charm. The most recent addition to Caltech's residential life is the Bechtel Residence, which opened its doors in 2018. It is distinctively not affiliated with the traditional house system, offering a different living experience [151]. All first- and second-year students are required to live on campus, either within the established house system or in the contemporary Bechtel Residence, ensuring a robust on-campus community for new students [152].

In a significant move reflecting evolving institutional values, the Caltech Board of Trustees, in January 2021, authorized the removal of Albert B. Ruddock's name from campus buildings [58]. This decision was made due to Ruddock's historical affiliation with the [Human Betterment Foundation](/Human_Betterment_Foundation), an organization associated with the eugenics movement. Consequently, Ruddock House was formally renamed as the Grant D. Venerable House, honoring Caltech's first Black graduate and marking a conscious effort to align campus nomenclature with principles of inclusivity and historical responsibility.

## Athletics

Caltech fields a diverse array of athletic teams, competing in disciplines such as baseball, men's and women's basketball, cross country, men's and women's soccer, swimming and diving, men's and women's tennis, track and field, women's volleyball, and men's and women's water polo [153]. The institution's mascot, the Beaver, is a rather fitting homage to nature's most industrious engineer, a symbol that resonates with Caltech's own dedication to ingenuity and hard work [154]. Caltech's teams are proud members of the [NCAA](/National_Collegiate_Athletic_Association) [Division III](/NCAA_Division_III) and compete within the [Southern California Intercollegiate Athletic Conference](/Southern_California_Intercollegiate_Athletic_Conference) (SCIAC), a conference that Caltech itself co-founded back in 1915, demonstrating a long-standing commitment to intercollegiate sports [155].

On January 6, 2007, a moment of profound, if understated, athletic triumph occurred: the Beavers' men's basketball team snapped an agonizing 207-game losing streak against Division III schools, securing a decisive 81–52 victory over [Bard College](/Bard_College). This marked their first Division III win since 1996, a testament to perseverance, if nothing else [156]. The team's struggles within SCIAC play were even more protracted; they had not secured a conference win since 1985. This drought finally ended on February 22, 2011, with a dramatic victory over [Occidental College](/Occidental_College) [157]. Ryan Elmquist's crucial free throw, sunk with just 3.3 seconds remaining in regulation, sealed the Beavers' hard-fought win [158] [159]. The often-challenging journey of the Beavers' 2005–06 season was even chronicled in the documentary film [Quantum Hoops](/Quantum_Hoops), offering a glimpse into the unique world of Caltech athletics.

Not to be outdone, the Caltech women's basketball team also achieved a significant milestone on January 13, 2007, when they broke a 50-game losing streak, triumphing over the [Pomona](/Pomona_College)-[Pitzer](/Pitzer_College) [Sagehens](/Pomona-Pitzer_Sagehens) with a final score of 55–53. This marked the women's program's inaugural conference win since joining the SCIAC in 2002. Adding a touch of academic celebrity to the occasion, [Robert Grubbs](/Robert_Grubbs), the distinguished 2005 Nobel laureate in Chemistry, served as honorary coach for the evening [160]. The team continued its momentum, securing a second SCIAC win against [Whittier College](/Whittier_College) on February 10, and notably, placed its first member on the All-Conference team [161].

Beyond the traditional NCAA sports, Caltech also boasts successful club teams. In 2007, 2008, and 2009, the women's table tennis team demonstrated its prowess by competing in nationals. The women's [Ultimate](/Ultimate_(sport)) club team, known with a certain panache as "Snatch," has also achieved considerable success in recent years, attaining a respectable ranking of 44 out of over 200 college teams within the Ultimate Player's Association [162].

Another long-standing losing streak was finally broken on February 2, 2013, when the Caltech baseball team ended a formidable 228-game skid, marking their first victory in almost a decade [163]. The track and field team's home venue is situated at the South Athletic Field within [Tournament Park](/Tournament_Park), a site of historical significance as it hosted the first eight [Rose Bowl](/Rose_Bowl_Game) games. The institution also, for a brief period from 1973 through 1977, sponsored an intercollegiate [football](/American_football) team [164] [165], even playing a portion of its home schedule at the iconic [Rose Bowl](/Rose_Bowl_(stadium)).

## Performing and visual arts

The Caltech/[Occidental College](/Occidental_College) Orchestra stands as a testament to inter-institutional collaboration, a full seventy-piece ensemble composed of talented students, faculty, and staff drawn from both Caltech and the nearby Occidental College. This impressive orchestra presents three pairs of concerts annually, performing alternately at both Caltech and Occidental College, enriching the cultural life of both campuses. Beyond the orchestral realm, Caltech also nurtures two distinct Jazz Bands and a Concert Band, alongside a notably active chamber music program, providing diverse opportunities for instrumentalists. For vocal enthusiasts, Caltech offers a mixed-voice [Glee Club](/Glee_Club) and the more intimate Chamber Singers, catering to various choral interests [166]. The institute's vibrant theater program, known by its acronym TACIT (Theater Arts at the California Institute of Technology), produces two to three plays each year, showcasing student and faculty talent. TACIT also notably contributed to the production of the [PHD Movie](/PHD_Comics), a film released in 2011 that resonated with the academic community.

## Student life traditions

### Annual events

Every [Halloween](/Halloween), Dabney House meticulously orchestrates the infamous "Millikan pumpkin-drop experiment," a tradition that, for some reason, persists. This rather dramatic event involves dropping pumpkins, often frozen in [liquid nitrogen](/Liquid_nitrogen) to ensure maximum theatricality, from the very top of what is now Caltech Hall (formerly the Millikan Library), the highest point on campus. The enduring tradition is rooted in a claim, made at some point in history, that the violent shattering of a liquid-nitrogen-frozen pumpkin, when dropped from a sufficient height, would produce a discernible [triboluminescent](/Triboluminescence) spark. This yearly spectacle draws a considerable crowd of observers, all eagerly, if often fruitlessly, attempting to spot the elusive spark. The event's title is, of course, an oblique and rather self-referential nod to [Robert Andrews Millikan](/Robert_Andrews_Millikan)'s much more significant [oil-drop experiment](/Oil-drop_experiment), which, unlike the pumpkin drop, actually measured *e*, the [elemental unit of electrical charge](/Elementary_charge). One might argue the scientific utility of the pumpkin drop is... debatable.

On Ditch Day, a truly unique Caltech tradition, the seniors, having endured their academic trials, symbolically "ditch" school. However, their departure is not without consequence for the underclassmen. They leave behind elaborately designed tasks and intricate "traps" at the entrances of their rooms, specifically engineered to prevent the younger students from gaining entry. Over the years, this ritual has evolved into an astonishing display of ingenuity, with many seniors dedicating months to conceptualizing and constructing complex mechanical, electrical, and software obstacles, all designed to confound and challenge the underclassmen. Each group of seniors crafts a "stack"—a series of puzzles and challenges—intended to be solved by a handful of underclassmen. Even the faculty have been drawn into this elaborate event, demonstrating a surprising level of institutional endorsement: all classes are officially canceled on Ditch Day, allowing the underclassmen to fully participate in what has become a highly anticipated highlight of the academic year.

Another venerable and somewhat aggressive tradition involves the playing of Wagner's "[Ride of the Valkyries](/Ride_of_the_Valkyries)" at precisely 7:00 AM each morning during finals week. This auditory assault is delivered with the largest, loudest speakers that can be procured, ensuring no student remains undisturbed. The playing of this specific piece of music is strictly prohibited at any other time (unless, of course, one is undertaking the heroic, or perhaps masochistic, endeavor of listening to the entire 14 hours and 5 minutes of [The Ring Cycle](/The_Ring_Cycle)). Any unfortunate offender caught violating this sacred rule is subjected to the rather unpleasant consequence of being dragged into the showers and drenched in cold water, fully dressed. A rather effective deterrent, one might concede.

## Pranks

Caltech students have, over the decades, cultivated a rather formidable reputation for their numerous and often ingenious [pranks](/Student_prank), colloquially known as "RFs" (Rigid Frames, a term borrowed from engineering, naturally) [167]. These are not mere hijinks, but often meticulously planned operations demonstrating a distinct intellectual flair.

Among the most celebrated pranks in recent history are two particularly audacious feats. One involved the clever alteration of the iconic [Hollywood Sign](/Hollywood_Sign) to read "Caltech," achieved by judiciously covering up specific parts of the letters. The other, a classic display of institutional pride and playful rivalry, occurred during the [1984 Rose Bowl Game](/1984_Rose_Bowl), where the scoreboard was surreptitiously changed to display "Caltech 38, MIT 9." However, arguably the most famous prank of all unfolded during the [1961 Rose Bowl Game](/1961_Rose_Bowl). In this legendary event, Caltech students ingeniously manipulated the flip-cards that were raised by stadium attendees, causing them to display "Caltech" and a series of other "unintended" messages, much to the confusion and eventual amusement of the crowd. This elaborate deception is now famously referred to as the [Great Rose Bowl Hoax](/Great_Rose_Bowl_Hoax).

In a somewhat surprising turn, in recent years, the art of pranking has received a degree of official encouragement from Tom Mannion, Caltech's Assistant VP for Student Affairs and Campus Life. As reported by the *Boston Globe*, Mannion explicitly stated, "The grand old days of pranking have gone away at Caltech, and that's what we are trying to bring back" [168]. This institutional endorsement suggests a recognition of pranking as a unique and valuable aspect of Caltech's vibrant student culture, fostering creativity and ingenuity.

In December 2011, a group of Caltech students extended their pranking prowess beyond the West Coast, executing a notable prank in Manhattan's [Greenwich Village](/Greenwich_Village). This particular stunt involved ingeniously transforming [The Cube](/Alamo_(sculpture)) sculpture, a well-known public art piece, to resemble the iconic [Aperture Science](/Aperture_Science) Weighted Companion Cube from the popular video game [Portal](/Portal_(video_game)) [169]. The meticulous planning and execution of such pranks are often documented and celebrated within the Caltech community. Indeed, Caltech pranks have been immortalized in a series of three "Legends of Caltech" books, the most recent edition of which was co-edited by alumni Autumn Looijen '99 and [Mason Porter](/Mason_Porter) '98 and published in May 2007, ensuring these acts of intellectual mischief are preserved for posterity.

## Rivalry with MIT

The rivalry between Caltech and [MIT](/Massachusetts_Institute_of_Technology) is legendary, a battle of wits and engineering prowess that manifests in increasingly elaborate and often hilarious pranks, a testament to the intellectual horsepower on both sides. In 2005, a group of Caltech students launched a series of calculated pranks during MIT's Campus Preview Weekend, a crucial recruitment event for admitted students. These included the rather pointed act of covering up the word "Massachusetts" in the "Massachusetts Institute of Technology" engraving on MIT's iconic main building façade with a banner, leaving it to read "That Other Institute of Technology." Not to be outdone, a group of [MIT hackers](/Hacks_at_the_Massachusetts_Institute_of_Technology) swiftly retaliated by altering the banner further, so the inscription now proclaimed "The Only Institute of Technology." Caltech students also distributed T-shirts to MIT's incoming freshman class, emblazoned with "MIT" on the front and the subtly cutting phrase "... because not everyone can go to Caltech" along with an image of a palm tree on the back, a gentle reminder of Southern California's superior climate.

MIT, with its own formidable hacking tradition, exacted its revenge in April 2006. Students, ingeniously posing as the "Howe & Ser (Howitzer) Moving Company," orchestrated the audacious theft of the 130-year-old, 1.7-ton Fleming House cannon. This rather heavy piece of equipment was then transported over 3,000 miles to their campus in Cambridge, Massachusetts, just in time for their 2006 Campus Preview Weekend. This particular prank echoed a similar feat performed by students from nearby [Harvey Mudd College](/Harvey_Mudd_College) in 1986. Unsurprisingly, thirty determined members of Fleming House embarked on a cross-country mission to MIT and successfully reclaimed their beloved cannon on April 10, 2006, demonstrating that some possessions are simply non-negotiable.

The intellectual skirmishes continued. On April 13, 2007 (a rather fitting Friday the 13th), a group of students from *The California Tech*, Caltech's campus newspaper, arrived at MIT and distributed meticulously crafted fake copies of *The Tech*, MIT's own campus newspaper, once again during their Campus Preview Weekend. The fabricated articles were a masterclass in deadpan humor, featuring headlines such as "MIT Invents the Interweb," "Architects Deem Campus 'Unfortunate'," and the delightfully absurd "[Infinite Corridor](/Infinite_Corridor) Not Actually Infinite." One can only imagine the bewildered expressions of prospective students.

In December 2009, Caltech students escalated the rivalry with a declaration that MIT had been officially sold and rebranded as the "Caltech East campus." A "sold" banner was conspicuously draped across the front of MIT's iconic dome building, and a "Welcome to Caltech East: School of the Humanities" banner was hung over the Massachusetts Avenue Entrance. To further cement the illusion, fake newspapers and T-shirts were distributed, and door labels and fliers detailing the "curriculum change" were strategically placed throughout the infinite corridor [170] [171].

The pranks even extended into the realm of science fiction. In September 2010, MIT students attempted to place a [TARDIS](/TARDIS), the iconic time machine from the BBC's *[Doctor Who](/Doctor_Who)*, onto a roof. This operation was, however, aborted mid-act. Not to let a good prop go to waste, in January 2011, Caltech students, in a rare moment of inter-institutional cooperation, assisted MIT students in successfully placing the TARDIS on top of Baxter Hall at Caltech [172]. The TARDIS then embarked on its own grand tour, subsequently being moved by Caltech students to [UC Berkeley](/UC_Berkeley) [173] and even [Stanford](/Stanford) [174], demonstrating its unexpected portability and the boundless energy of Caltech's pranksters.

The rivalry resurfaced in April 2014, once again during MIT's Campus Preview Weekend, when a group of Caltech students distributed coffee mugs. These deceptively simple mugs were emblazoned with the MIT logo on the front and the words "The Institute of Technology" on the back. The true genius, or perhaps cruelty, of the prank was revealed when the mugs were heated: they would turn a vibrant orange, display a palm tree, and then declare, "Caltech The Hotter Institute of Technology." These identical, subtly insulting mugs, one notes, continue to be sold at the Caltech campus store [175], serving as a permanent, if petty, reminder of the ongoing intellectual skirmish.

## Honor code

Life within the rigorous and intellectually demanding Caltech community is fundamentally governed by a concise yet profoundly impactful [honor code](/Academic_honor_code). Its statement is deceptively simple: "No member of the Caltech community shall take unfair advantage of any other member of the Caltech community." This foundational principle aims to cultivate an atmosphere of profound respect and mutual trust, a cornerstone that, in turn, allows Caltech students to enjoy a unique suite of privileges designed to foster a more relaxed and intellectually stimulating environment [176]. For instance, the honor code famously empowers professors to assign the majority of examinations as take-home assessments, affording students the autonomy to complete them on their own schedule and within their preferred environment, a luxury rarely found in other top-tier institutions.

The enforcement of this honor code is meticulously overseen by a dedicated Board of Control, composed entirely of undergraduate students [176], ensuring peer accountability. A parallel body, known as the Graduate Honor Council, performs a similar function at the graduate level [177]. These student-led bodies are central to maintaining the integrity of the system.

However, the purity of the honor code, once considered almost sacrosanct, has, in recent decades, faced certain challenges and perceived compromises. Through the late 1990s, the sole exception to the honor code, implemented earlier in the decade in response to evolving federal regulations, pertained to the sexual harassment policy. Today, the landscape is considerably more complex, with a "myriad exceptions" manifesting in the form of new Institute policies, such as specific guidelines regarding fire safety and alcohol consumption. While both these policies are dutifully outlined in the Honor System Handbook provided to all new members of the Caltech community, some undergraduates view them as a subtle, yet significant, slight against the core tenets of the honor code itself, and the implicit trust and respect it traditionally represents within the community [178]. Furthermore, in recent years, the Student Affairs Office has, on occasion, undertaken investigations independently of the Board of Control and the Conduct Review Committee. This practice, perceived by some as an implicit violation of both the spirit of the honor code and established disciplinary policy, has unfortunately contributed to a further erosion of trust between certain segments of the undergraduate community and the administration [179]. Such tensions, though perhaps minor in the grand scheme, highlight the ongoing challenge of maintaining an idealized system in a complex, evolving institutional environment.

# Notable people

As of October 2025, Caltech boasts an astonishing 48 [Nobel laureates](/Nobel_Prize) affiliated with the institution, a testament to its profound impact on scientific discovery. These prestigious awards have been distributed among 26 alumni, 5 postdoctoral scholars, and 17 non-alumni professors. Among the 26 alumni who have received the Nobel Prize, five also served as distinguished Caltech professors: [Carl D. Anderson](/Carl_D._Anderson), [Linus Pauling](/Linus_Pauling), [William A. Fowler](/William_A._Fowler), [Edward B. Lewis](/Edward_B._Lewis), and [Kip Thorne](/Kip_Thorne). Of the 17 non-alumni professors who are Nobel laureates, 14 were actively in residence at Caltech at the time of their award, further underscoring the institute's vibrant research environment. [David Baltimore](/David_Baltimore), who shared the Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1975, later assumed the presidency of Caltech in 1997. Notably, [Renato Dulbecco](/Renato_Dulbecco), who also shared the Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1975, explicitly credited his time spent at Caltech as foundational to his award-winning work [180]. More recently, John Hopfield, who was awarded the Prize in Physics in 2024, holds the distinguished title of Dickinson Professor Emeritus at Caltech [181]. The total count of Nobel Prizes associated with Caltech reaches 49, a unique distinction attributed to [Linus Pauling](/Linus_Pauling), who, in an unparalleled achievement, received Nobel Prizes in both [Chemistry](/Nobel_Prizel_in_Chemistry) and [Peace](/Nobel_Peace_Prize) [182]. Beyond the Nobel, Caltech affiliations extend to eight faculty and alumni who have been honored with a [Crafoord Prize](/Crafoord_Prize) from the [Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences](/Royal_Swedish_Academy_of_Sciences), while a remarkable 58 individuals have been awarded the U.S. [National Medal of Science](/National_Medal_of_Science), and 11 have received the prestigious [National Medal of Technology](/National_Medal_of_Technology) [4]. The institution also counts one alumnus, [Stanislav Smirnov](/Stanislav_Smirnov), among the elite recipients of the [Fields Medal](/Fields_Medal), which he was awarded in 2010. Furthermore, Caltech has been a temporary intellectual home for numerous other distinguished researchers who have graced its campus as postdoctoral scholars (including luminaries such as [Barbara McClintock](/Barbara_McClintock), [James D. Watson](/James_D._Watson), [Sheldon Glashow](/Sheldon_Glashow), and [John Gurdon]) or as highly respected visiting professors (a list that includes [Albert Einstein](/Albert_Einstein), [Stephen Hawking](/Stephen_Hawking), and [Edward Witten])—a testament to its enduring magnetic pull for the world's brightest minds.

## Alumni

Caltech boasts a global network of 22,930 living alumni, a testament to its enduring impact on scientific and technological leadership worldwide [183]. As of October 2022, this distinguished group includes 30 alumni and 16 non-alumni faculty who have been awarded the prestigious [Nobel Prize](/Nobel_Prize). Furthermore, the [Turing Award](/Turing_Award), often reverently referred to as the "Nobel Prize of Computer Science," has been bestowed upon six Caltech alumni, and one alumnus has achieved the pinnacle of mathematical recognition, the [Fields Medal](/Fields_Medal) [184].

Many Caltech alumni have dedicated their formidable intellects to pioneering [scientific research](/Scientific_research), pushing the boundaries of human understanding. Some have focused their studies on the intricate, very small universe of atoms and molecules, unraveling the fundamental building blocks of existence. [Nobel laureate](/Nobel_Prize) [Carl D. Anderson](/Carl_D._Anderson) (BS 1927, PhD 1930) famously provided empirical proof for the existence of [positrons](/Positron) and [muons](/Muon), fundamentally altering our understanding of subatomic particles. Fellow Nobel laureate [Edwin McMillan](/Edwin_McMillan) (BS 1928, MS 1929) achieved the significant feat of synthesizing the first [transuranium element](/Transuranium_element), expanding the periodic table. [Leo James Rainwater](/Leo_James_Rainwater) (BS 1939), another Nobel laureate, conducted groundbreaking investigations into the non-spherical shapes of atomic nuclei, revealing unexpected complexities in nuclear structure. More recently, Nobel laureate [Douglas D. Osheroff](/Douglas_D._Osheroff) (BS 1967) delved into the exotic realm of condensed matter physics, studying the fascinating [superfluid](/Superfluid) nature of [helium-3](/Helium-3). In the digital domain, [Donald Knuth](/Donald_Knuth) (PhD 1963), widely hailed as the "father" of the [analysis of algorithms](/Analysis_of_algorithms), authored the seminal multi-volume work *[The Art of Computer Programming](/The_Art_of_Computer_Programming)* and created the influential [TeX](/TeX) computer typesetting system, which remains a standard tool in the scientific community. [Bruce Reznick](/Bruce_Reznick) (BS 1973) is a distinguished mathematician renowned for his significant contributions to [number theory](/Number_theory) and his comprehensive combinatorial-algebraic-analytic investigations of polynomials. [Narendra Karmarkar](/Narendra_Karmarkar) (MS 1979) is celebrated for developing the interior point method, a polynomial algorithm for linear programming that became famously known as [Karmarkar's algorithm](/Karmarkar%27s_algorithm).

Other alumni have, with equal ambition, turned their gaze towards the vast expanse of the universe, contributing profoundly to space exploration and astronomy. [C. Gordon Fullerton](/C._Gordon_Fullerton) (BS 1957, MS 1958) achieved distinction as the pilot of the third [Space Shuttle](/Space_Shuttle) mission, a critical early flight. Astronaut (and later, a [United States Senator](/United_States_Senate)) [Harrison Schmitt](/Harrison_Schmitt) (BS 1957) holds the unique distinction of being the only geologist to have walked on the surface of the Moon, bringing invaluable scientific perspective to lunar exploration [185]. The esteemed astronomer [Eugene Merle Shoemaker](/Eugene_Merle_Shoemaker) (BS 1947, MS 1948) co-discovered [Comet Shoemaker-Levy 9](/Comet_Shoemaker-Levy_9), a celestial body that famously collided with the planet [Jupiter](/Jupiter). In a poignant and unique tribute, Shoemaker became the first person to be "buried" on the Moon, with his ashes intentionally crashed into the lunar surface [186]. Astronomer George O. Abell (BS 1951, MS 1952, PhD 1957), while a graduate student at Caltech, played a crucial role in the National Geographic Society-Palomar Sky Survey, an monumental undertaking that ultimately led to the publication of the definitive *Abell Catalogue of Clusters of Galaxies*, a foundational work in the field of extragalactic astronomy [187].

The entrepreneurial spirit is also deeply embedded in the Caltech alumni community. Undergraduate alumni have founded, or co-founded, several influential companies, including the [LCD](/LCD) manufacturer Varitronix (co-founded by [York Liao](/York_Liao), BS 1967) [188], the pioneering webmail service [Hotmail](/Hotmail) (co-founded by [Sabeer Bhatia](/Sabeer_Bhatia), BS 1991) [189], the computer giant [Compaq](/Compaq) (co-founded by [Benjamin Rosen](/Benjamin_Rosen), BS 1954) [190], [MathWorks](/MathWorks) (the creators of [Matlab](/Matlab), co-founded by [Cleve Moler](/Cleve_Moler), BS 1961) [191], and the modern database provider [Imply](/Imply_Data) [192]. Graduate students, not to be outdone, have also been instrumental in the creation of significant enterprises, such as [Intel](/Intel) (co-founded by [Gordon Moore](/Gordon_Moore), PhD 1954) [193], [TRW](/TRW_Inc.) (co-founded by [Simon Ramo](/Simon_Ramo), PhD 1936) [194], and the highly influential non-profit educational organization, the [Exploratorium](/Exploratorium) (founded by [Frank Oppenheimer](/Frank_Oppenheimer), PhD 1939) [195].

[Arnold Beckman](/Arnold_Orville_Beckman) (PhD 1928), a truly visionary alumnus, invented the groundbreaking [pH meter](/PH_meter), a device that revolutionized chemical analysis. He subsequently commercialized this innovation through the founding of [Beckman Instruments](/Beckman_Instruments), building a highly successful enterprise. His success with Beckman Instruments enabled him to provide crucial seed funding to [William Shockley](/William_Shockley) (BS 1932), who, as a co-inventor of [semiconductor](/Semiconductor) [transistors](/Transistor), sought to commercialize this transformative technology. Shockley subsequently became the founding Director of the [Shockley Semiconductor Laboratory](/Shockley_Semiconductor_Laboratory) division of Beckman Instruments [196]. Shockley, who had previously worked at the esteemed [Bell Labs](/Bell_Labs) (whose first president was another Caltech alumnus, [Frank Jewett](/Frank_B._Jewett), BS 1898), chose to establish his laboratory in [Mountain View, California](/Mountain_View,_California), near [Palo Alto, California](/Palo_Alto,_California), to be close to his aging mother [196] [197]. While Shockley was a co-recipient of the [Nobel Prize in Physics](/Nobel_Prizel_in_Physics) in 1956, his aggressive management style and rather unconventional personality [198] at the Shockley Lab ultimately became unbearable for many of his brilliant researchers [199]. In late 1957, eight of these frustrated researchers famously resigned and, with crucial support from [Sherman Fairchild](/Sherman_Fairchild), went on to form